"Kamel T., Mitachi K., Kato Y., Furukawa K.","Feasibility study on smooth shift from LWR to THORIMS-NES; a mass balance calculation of fissile materials and minor actinide",2009,"Electrochemistry","77","8",,"594","596",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-70350120019&partnerID=40&md5=caf493bf52f7b8f3a36913162e85708c","Institute of Sustainability Science, Kyoto University, Gokasho, Uji 611-0011, Japan; Department of Mechanical Engineering, Toyohashi University of Technology, Tempaku-cho, Toyohashi 441-8580, Japan; International Thorium Molten-Salt Forum, Ibaraki, Japan; International Thorium Molten-Salt Forum, Kanagawa, Japan","Kamel, T., Institute of Sustainability Science, Kyoto University, Gokasho, Uji 611-0011, Japan; Mitachi, K., Department of Mechanical Engineering, Toyohashi University of Technology, Tempaku-cho, Toyohashi 441-8580, Japan; Kato, Y., International Thorium Molten-Salt Forum, Ibaraki, Japan; Furukawa, K., International Thorium Molten-Salt Forum, Kanagawa, Japan","Nuclear energy is reconsidered against global warming but the concerns (nuclear proliferation, radioactive waste, safety etc.) make it difficult to apply widely in the world. To comprehensively solve these difficulties, we have proposed Th-233U fuel cycle named THORIMS-NES (Thorium molten-salt nuclear energy synergetics). We calculated the mass balance of fissile materials and the production of minor actinide (MA) governing major part of radioactive waste for evaluating the smooth shift to Th-233U fuel cycle. Th- 233U fuel cycle can generate 3 TWe at around 2050 and 10 TWe at around the end of this century by applying Pu obtained from spent nuclear fuel of conventional nuclear system and 233U produced by Accelerator Molten-Salt Breeders (AMSB).","Mass balance analysis; Molten-salt reactor; Thorium utilization; Transition","Feasibility studies; Fissile materials; Fuel cycle; Mass balance; Mass balance analysis; Mass-balance calculations; Minor actinide; Molten-salt reactor; Nuclear proliferation; Nuclear systems; Spent nuclear fuels; Synergetics; Transition; Global warming; Industrial waste treatment; Nuclear energy; Nuclear fuels; Planning; Plutonium; Radioactive wastes; Radioactivity; Resource allocation; Thorium; Energy conversion",,,,,,"Furukawa, K., Lecocq, A., Kato, Y., Mitachi, K., (1990) J. Nucl. Sci. Tech., 27, p. 1157; Furukawa, K., Numata, H., Kato, Y., Mitachi, K., Yoshioka, R., Furuhashi, A., (2005) Electrochemistry, 73, p. 552; Furukawa, K., Arakawa, K., Erbay, L.B., Ito, Y., Kato, Y., Kiyavitskaya, H., Lecocq, A., Yoshioka, R., (2008) Ene. Conversion and Manag, 49, p. 1832; (2008), http://www.regjeringen.no/upload/OED/Rapporter/ThoriumReport2008.pdfFuture Summit Report, Future Summit 2008, p.8 (2008)Honma, Y., Shimazu, Y., (2007) TU2007; Mitachi, K., Yamamoto, T., Yoshioka, R., Sugimoto, T., (2008) Trans. Atom. Energy Soc. Jpn, 7, p. 127; (2003) Nuclear2001, p. 184. , OECD-IEA; Uhlir, J., Mareček, M., Precek, M., (2008) Atalante 2008; Machacek, V., Peka, I., Vessely, V., Chochlovsky, I., (1982) Proc. ANS, p. 121; Furukawa, K., Tsukada, K., Nakahara, Y., (1981) J. Nucl. Sci. Tech., 18, p. 79; Furukawa, K., Chigrinov, S., Kato, Y., Mitachi, K., (1994) Emerg. Nucl. Energy Systems World Sei., p. 429","Kamel, T.; Institute of Sustainability Science, Kyoto University, Gokasho, Uji 611-0011, Japan",,,,,,,,13443542,,EECTF,,"English","Electrochem",Article,Scopus,2-s2.0-70350120019
